  "body": "Average residential rent prices rose 11 per cent in 2025, yet Abu Dhabi announced a temporary rent freeze across the city on Tuesday, June 2, effective immediately. All residential, commercial, and industrial tenancy contract renewals will be processed at a 0 per cent increase for the duration of the measure. Any new tenancy contract on a previously rented unit will be offered at the same rental value as the preceding contract, with a freeze on price increase.\n\nThe announcement represents a dramatic departure from the regulatory framework that has governed Abu Dhabi's rental market for a decade. An annual cap has been in place in Abu Dhabi since 2016, preventing landlords from raising rent by more than 5 per cent when tenancies are renewed. The freeze—which is temporary and until further notice—eliminates that 5 per cent allowance entirely, creating a structural compression in landlord returns and a corresponding relief for tenants navigating an increasingly constrained housing market.\n\nThe timing of this intervention is not incidental. Abu Dhabi's rental market remained very tight, driven by strong population growth and limited available homes. Just 13 percent of the expected 2026 residential supply materialised in the first quarter, according to ValuStrat, and no acceleration is projected until after 2028. This supply-demand imbalance has created acute affordability pressures—precisely the catalyst that prompted the Abu Dhabi Real Estate Centre's decision. The rent freeze comes as many people in the UAE struggle with rising prices, with some losing their jobs or facing salary reductions, linked to the Iran war.\n\nFor tenants, the mandate is unambiguous. One Abu Dhabi resident, Shehla Sohail, said her tenancy renewal was processed recently and included a 5 per cent rent increase, but the move will definitely bring relief to many residents facing renewals in the coming months. Abu Dhabi resident Melanie Nazareno, 37, said the decision offered \"certainty and peace of mind\" and would ease the financial strain on families in the capital. This certainty—the ability to forecast housing costs without the volatility that has characterised recent years—addresses a fundamental concern for UHNW investors and owner-occupiers alike.\n\nYet the freeze's implications for landlords are more nuanced than a simple loss of rental income. Andry Grouta, property consultant at MD Real Estate, noted that for some landlords it ensures that their tenants will stay where they are for this reason. Ben Crompton, managing partner of Crompton Partners, told The National that \"realistically there was only a 5 per cent increase in place before, so it's not a huge bonus but it's something\". The freeze thus presents a trade-off: landlords sacrifice near-term rental growth in exchange for tenant retention and reduced vacancy risk—a calculus that may favour long-term portfolio stability over short-term yield compression.\n\nA critical architectural feature of the freeze is its application through the Tawtheeq system, Abu Dhabi's digital registration framework. When a landlord enters the new rent in the Tawtheeq system, it will not allow them to put in any higher rent, even if a tenant has agreed to a rate increase prior to this rule. This technical enforcement mechanism—blocking contracts at the registration layer—prevents workarounds and ensures the freeze's mandate is binding across the entire precinct.\n\nThe freeze's scope is comprehensive but not universal. A representative for the real estate centre told The National the rental freeze \"does not include the ADGM jurisdiction as they are on a different legal framework and governance\", and ADGM communities were the only exception to the rental freeze. This carve-out preserves the Abu Dhabi Global Market's sovereign-backed regulatory autonomy while extending the freeze across the broader emirate.\n\nMarket observers describe the move as structurally unprecedented. Real estate experts have welcomed the move by Abu Dhabi to temporarily freeze rents, with one industry veteran describing the move as \"extremely rare\" on a global scale. The freeze's duration remains the critical unknown variable. The longer it continues, the more likely it is that some landlords will change contracts or choose not to renew tenancies. Yet for now, the measure provides both tenants and landlords with the market transparency and contractual predictability that has been absent in Abu Dhabi's increasingly volatile rental absorption.",
